{"title_page": "Stephanorhinus", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = Pliocene to Late [[Pleistocene]] {{fossil range|5|0.04}}\n| image = Stephanorhinus etruscus skeleton 23.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Stephanorhinus etruscus'' skeleton\n| taxon = Stephanorhinus\n| authority = [[Mikl\u00f3s Kretzoi|Kretzoi]], 1942\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *\u2020''S. etruscus'' (Falconer, 1868) Etruscan rhinoceros\n*\u2020''S. jeanvireti'' (Falconer, 1859)\n*\u2020''S. hundsheimensis'' (Toula, 1902) Hundsheim rhinoceros\n*\u2020''S. hemitoechus'' (Falconer, 1859) Narrow-nosed rhinoceros\n*\u2020''S. kirchbergensis'' (J\u00e4ger, 1839) Merck's rhinoceros\n}}\n\n'''''Stephanorhinus''''' is an [[extinct]] genus of two-horned [[rhinoceros]] native to northern [[Eurasia]] and possibly North Africa that lived during the [[Pliocene]] to [[Late Pleistocene]]. Two species of ''Stephanorhinus'', [[Merck's rhinoceros]] ''S. kirchbergensis'' and the narrow-nosed rhinoceros ''S. hemitoechus'' persisted into the [[Last Glacial Period|last glacial period]], with the last record for the latter being around 40,000 years ago in [[Bacho Kiro cave]] in Bulgaria.<ref>Stuart, A.J., Lister, A.M., 2007. Patterns of Late Quaternary megafaunal extinctions in Europe and northern Asia. In: Kahlke, R.-D., Maul, L.C., Mazza, P. (Eds.), Late Neogene and Quaternary Biodiversity and Evolution: Regional Developments and Interregional Correlations Vol. II, Proceedings of the 18th International Senckenberg Conference (VI International Palaeontological Colloquium in Weimar). Courier Forschungsinstitut Senckenberg 259, pp. 287-297.</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe first part of the name is derived from that of [[Stephen I of Hungary|King Stephen I of Hungary]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Tong|first=HaoWen|last2=Wu|first2=XianZhu|date=April 2010|title=Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia) from the Rhino Cave in Shennongjia, Hubei|journal=Chinese Science Bulletin|language=en|volume=55|issue=12|pages=1157\u20131168|bibcode=2010ChSBu..55.1157T|doi=10.1007/s11434-010-0050-5|issn=1001-6538}}</ref> and the second part from ''''rhinos'''' (\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2, meaning \"[[nose]]\"), as with ''Dicerorhinus.''\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe taxonomic history of ''Stephanorhinus'' is long and convoluted, as many species are known by numerous synonyms and different genera, typically ''Rhinoceros'' and ''Dicerorhinus'' for the 19th and most of the early 20th century. The genus was named by [[Mikl\u00f3s Kretzoi]] in 1942.<ref>Mikl\u00f3s Kretzoi: ''[http://epa.oszk.hu/01600/01635/00420/pdf/ Bemerkungen zur System der Nachmioz\u00e4nen Nashorn-Gattungen (Comments on the system of the post Miocene rhinoceros genera)]''  [[F\u00f6ldtani K\u00f6zl\u00f6ny|F\u00f6ldtani K\u00f6zl\u00f6ni]], Budapest 72 (4-12), 1942, S. 309\u2013318</ref> It is thought that ''Stephanorhinus'' is more closely related to the [[Sumatran rhinoceros]] and [[woolly rhinoceros]] than other rhino species. A complete mitochondrial genome of ''S. kirchbergensis'' obtained from a 70,000 - 48,000 year old skull preserved in permafrost in arctic [[Yakutia]] showed that it was more closely related to the woolly rhinoceros than the Sumatran rhinoceros.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kirillova|first=Irina V.|last2=Chernova|first2=Olga F.|last3=van der Made|first3=Jan|last4=Kukarskih|first4=Vladimir V.|last5=Shapiro|first5=Beth|last6=van der Plicht|first6=Johannes|last7=Shidlovskiy|first7=Fedor K.|last8=Heintzman|first8=Peter D.|last9=van Kolfschoten|first9=Thijs|last10=Zanina|first10=Oksana G.|date=November 2017|title=Discovery of the skull of Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis (J\u00e4ger, 1839) above the Arctic Circle|journal=Quaternary Research|language=en|volume=88|issue=3|pages=537\u2013550|bibcode=2017QuRes..88..537K|doi=10.1017/qua.2017.53|issn=0033-5894}}</ref>  In 2019 a study of dental proteomes showed that the genus was [[Paraphyly|paraphyletic]] as currently defined, as the genus ''[[Coelodonta]]'' was found to be derived from an early diverging lineage within ''Stephanorhinus'', with the proteome sequence obtained from the enamel of a 1.77 million year old ''Stephanorhinus'' sp''.'' tooth from [[Dmanisi historic site|Dmanisi]] outside the clade containing the woolly rhinoceros and ''S. kirchbergensis.''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cappellini|first=Enrico|last2=Welker|first2=Frido|last3=Pandolfi|first3=Luca|last4=Ramos-Madrigal|first4=Jazm\u00edn|last5=Samodova|first5=Diana|last6=R\u00fcther|first6=Patrick L.|last7=Fotakis|first7=Anna K.|last8=Lyon|first8=David|last9=Moreno-Mayar|first9=J. V\u00edctor|last10=Bukhsianidze|first10=Maia|last11=Rakownikow Jersie-Christensen|first11=Rosa|displayauthors=10|date=October 2019|title=Early Pleistocene enamel proteome from Dmanisi resolves Stephanorhinus phylogeny|url=|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=574|issue=7776|pages=103\u2013107|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1555-y|issn=0028-0836|pmc=6894936|pmid=31511700|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Species and evolution==\nThe oldest known species of the genus are from the Pliocene of Europe, the species ''S. pikermiensis'' and ''S. megarhinus'' that were formerly considered to belong to ''Stephanorhinus'' are currently considered to belong to ''[[Dihoplus]].''<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|title=Evolutionary history of Rhinocerotina  (Mammalia, Perissodactyla)|date=2018|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.32774/fosreppal.20.1810.102732|work=Fossilia - Reports in Palaeontology|pages=27\u201332|publisher=Saverio Bartolini Lucenti|isbn=979-12-200-3408-1|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Rivals|first2=Florent|last3=Rabinovich|first3=Rivka|date=January 2020|title=A new species of rhinoceros from the site of Bethlehem: \u2018Dihoplus\u2019 bethlehemsis sp. nov. (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1040618220300124|journal=Quaternary International|language=en|volume=537|pages=48\u201360|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2020.01.011}}</ref>\n[[File:Stephanorhinus jeanvireti skull.jpg|left|thumb|Skull of ''Stephanorhinus jeanvireti'']]\n''Stephanorhinus jeanvireti,'' also known as ''S. elatus''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ballatore|first=Manuel|last2=Breda|first2=Marzia|date=December 2016|title=Stephanorhinus elatus (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia): proposal for the conservation of the earlier specific name and designation of a lectotype|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/10.5252/g2016n4a7|journal=Geodiversitas|language=en|volume=38|issue=4|pages=579\u2013594|doi=10.5252/g2016n4a7|issn=1280-9659}}</ref> Is known from the Late Pliocene and Early Pleistocene of Europe. Its remains are relatively rare in comparison to other ''Stephanorhinus'' species. Specimens are known from the Late Pliocene of Germany<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lacombat|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last2=M\u00f6rs|first2=Thomas|date=2008-08-01|title=The northernmost occurrence of the rare Late Pliocene rhinoceros Stephanorhinus jeanvireti (Mammalia, Perissodactyla)|url=http://openurl.ingenta.com/content/xref?genre=article&issn=0077-7749&volume=249&issue=2&spage=157|journal=Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie - Abhandlungen|language=en|volume=249|issue=2|pages=157\u2013165|doi=10.1127/0077-7749/2008/0249-0157}}</ref> France, Italy,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|date=October 2013|title=New and revised occurrences of Dihoplus megarhinus (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) in the Pliocene of Italy|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s13358-013-0056-0|journal=Swiss Journal of Palaeontology|volume=132|issue=2|pages=239\u2013255|doi=10.1007/s13358-013-0056-0|issn=1664-2376}}</ref> Slovakia<ref>\u0160ujan, M., Ryb\u00e1r, S., \u0160arinov\u00e1, K., Kov\u00e1\u010d, M., Vla\u010diky, M., Zervanov\u00e1, J., 2013. [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236974033_Uppermost_Miocene_to_Quaternary_accumulation_history_at_the_Danube_Basin_eastern_flanks Uppermost Miocene to Quaternary accumulation history at the Danube Basin eastern flanks], in: Fodor, L., K\u00f6v\u00e9r, Sz. (eds.), 11th Meeting of the Central European Tectonic Studies Group (CETeG). Abstract book, Geol. Geophys. Inst. of Hungary, Budapest, pp. 66-68.</ref> and Greece,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=Claude|last2=Tsoukala|first2=Evangelia|date=June 2013|title=The Tapiridae, Rhinocerotidae and Suidae (Mammalia) of the Early Villafranchian site of Milia (Grevena, Macedonia, Greece)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5252/g2013n2a7|journal=Geodiversitas|volume=35|issue=2|pages=447\u2013489|doi=10.5252/g2013n2a7|issn=1280-9659}}</ref> and the Early Pleistocene of Romania.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Codrea|first2=Vlad A.|last3=Popescu|first3=Aurelian|date=December 2019|title=Stephanorhinus jeanvireti (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) from the early Pleistocene of Col\u021be\u0219ti (southwestern Romania)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1631068319301319|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=18|issue=8|pages=1041\u20131056|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2019.07.004}}</ref>[[File:Stephanorhinus etruscus skull.JPG|left|thumb|Skull of  ''Stephanorhinus etruscus'']]''Stephanorhinus etruscus'' first appears in the latest Pliocene in the Iberian Peninsula, around 3.3 Ma at [[:es:Yacimiento de Las Higueruelas|Las Higueruelas]] in Spain and before 3 Ma at [[Piedrabuena]], and during the latest Pliocene at Villafranca d\u2019Asti and Castelnuovo di Barardenga in Italy and is abundant during most of the [[Villafranchian]] period in Europe, and is the sole rhinoceros species in Europe between 2.5 to around 1.3 Ma. A specimen is known from the Early Pleistocene (1.6-1.2 Ma) [[Ubeidiya]] locality in Israel. During the late Early Pleistocene it is largely replaced by ''S. hundsheimensis''. The last known records of the species are from the latest Early Pleistocene of the Iberian peninsula, around 0.9-0.8 Ma.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Cerde\u00f1o|first2=Esperanza|last3=Codrea|first3=Vlad|last4=Kotsakis|first4=Tassos|date=September 2017|title=Biogeography and chronology of the Eurasian extinct rhinoceros Stephanorhinus etruscus (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1631068317300702|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=16|issue=7|pages=762\u2013773|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2017.06.004}}</ref>\n\n''Stephanorhinus yunchuchenensis'' is known from a single specimen in Early Pleistocene deposits in [[Yushe County]], [[Shaanxi]] while ''Stephanorhinus lantianensis'' is also known from a single specimen from late Early Pleistocene (1.15 Ma) deposits in [[Lantian County]], Shaanxi.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Tong|first=Hao-wen|date=November 2012|title=Evolution of the non-Coelodonta dicerorhine lineage in China|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1631068312000838|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=11|issue=8|pages=555\u2013562|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2012.06.002}}</ref> These are stated to be synonyms of ''Stephanorhinus'' ''kirchbergensis'' by some sources.<ref name=\"Antoine 2011\" />\n\nThe first record of ''Stephanorhinus'' ''kirchbergensis'' is in China at [[Zhoukoudian|Choukoutien]] Locality 13, in [[Fangshan District]] near Beijing which is around the Early-Mid Pleistocene transition at 0.8 Ma.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis skull.jpg|left|thumb|Skull of ''Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis'']]\n''Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis'' first defintively appears in the fossil record in Europe and Anatolia at around 1.2 Ma, with possible records in Iberia around 1.6 Ma and 1.4-1.3 Ma. The earliest confirmed appearance in Italy around 1 Ma.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Erten|first2=H\u00fcseyin|date=January 2017|title=Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) from the late early Pleistocene deposits of the Denizli Basin (Anatolia, Turkey)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0016699516301243|journal=Geobios|language=en|volume=50|issue=1|pages=65\u201373|doi=10.1016/j.geobios.2016.10.002}}</ref> The diet of ''S. hundsheimensis'' was flexible and ungeneralised, with two different early Middle Pleistocene populations under different climactic regimes having tooth wear analyses suggesting contrasting browsing and grazing habits.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kahlke|first=Ralf-Dietrich|last2=Kaiser|first2=Thomas M.|date=August 2011|title=Generalism as a subsistence strategy: advantages and limitations of the highly flexible feeding traits of Pleistocene Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0277379109004314|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=30|issue=17-18|pages=2250\u20132261|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2009.12.012}}</ref> The more specialised ''S. kirchbergensis'' and ''S. hemiotoechus'',, appear in Europe between 0.7-6 Ma and 0.6-0.5 Ma respectively, and largely displace ''S. hundsheimensis. S. kirchbergensis'' and ''S. hemiotoechus'' are typically interpreted as a browsing form and grazing form, respectively. The evolution of more specialized diets is possibly due to the change to the 100 Kyr cycle after the [[Mid-Pleistocene Transition|Mid Pleistocene Transition]], which resulted in environmental stability allowing the development of more specialsed forms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Asperen|first=Eline N.|last2=Kahlke|first2=Ralf-Dietrich|date=January 2015|title=Dietary variation and overlap in Central and Northwest European Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis and S. hemitoechus (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia) influenced by habitat diversity|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0277379114003886|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=107|pages=47\u201361|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2014.10.001}}</ref>\n[[File:Skulls of pleistocene rhinos.png|left|thumb|Skulls from top to bottom. ''S. kirchbergensis, S. hemitoechus'' and the woolly rhinoceros, showing the difference in head angle]]\n\nFrom the late Middle Pleistocene onwards, the large Merck's rhinoceros (''[[Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis]]'') and the narrow-nosed rhinoceros (''[[Stephanorhinus hemitoechus]]'') were the only species of ''Stephanorhinus''. ''Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis'' preferred forest or woodland habitats, while ''S. hemitoechus'' was probably adapted to more open habitats.<ref name=\"Pushkina 2007\">Diana Pushkina: ''The Pleistocene easternmost distribution in Eurasia of the species associated with the Eemian'' Palaeoloxodon antiquus ''assemblage.'' Mammal Review, 2007.\nVolume 37 Issue 3, Pages 224 - 245</ref> ''S. kirchbergensis'' is relatively rare in fossil record and known from few Italian, French, German, British, and East-European localities, mostly of the middle Pleistocene. In Asia it is known from [[Siberia]], [[Central Asia]] (e.g. southeastern [[Kazakhstan]]), [[Central Korea]], and [[China]]. It may have also occurred in [[Israel]] and [[Lebanon]], but here it is unclear if it was really ''S. kirchbergensis'' or a similar species.<ref>Emmanuel M.E. Billia: ''Revision of the fossil material attributed to ''Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis'' (J\u00e4ger 1839) (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) preserved in the museum collections of the Russian Federation''. Quaternary International. Volume 179, Issue 1, March 2008, Pages 25-37</ref> In [[eastern China]], ''S. kirchbergensis'' was present throughout the Pleistocene between 30\u00b0N and 40\u00b0N.<ref name=\"Antoine 2011\">Pierre Olivier Antoine: ''Pleistocene and holocene rhinocerotids (Mammalia, Perissodactyla) from the Indochinese Peninsula.'' In: ''Comptes Rendus Palevol.'' 2011, S. 1\u201310.</ref> It is stated by some sources that ''S. hemitoechus'' occurs in North Africa.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn eastern Europe ''S. kirchbergensis'' disappeared during the earliest Late Pleistocene, where it is recorded in the [[Eemian]] in Poland. In the forests of the [[Caucasus]] it may have survived even until the early [[Weichselian]]. The last occurrences are known from [[Spain]], where it survived until the middle or early Late Weichselian. The narrow-nosed rhinoceros appeared in Europe in the early Middle Pleistocene. It is known here from many localities between, Spain, [[Italy]], [[Germany]] and the [[British Islands]]. Apart from Europe it is also known from [[Syria]], Israel, the Caucasus and from one Late Pleistocene locality close to [[Lake Baikal]]. This is the easternmost point of the known range. The latest fossils of the narrow-nosed rhinoceros are known from the [[Balkans]], where it survived until the early late Weichselian.<ref name=\"Pushkina 2007\"/>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14551210}}\n\n[[Category:Pleistocene rhinoceroses]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene genus extinctions]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric mammals of Europe]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = Pliocene to Late [[Pleistocene]] {{fossil range|5|0.04}}\n| image = Stephanorhinus etruscus skeleton 23.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Stephanorhinus.etruscus'' skeleton\n| taxon = Stephanorhinus\n| authority = [[Mikl\u00f3s Kretzoi|Kretzoi]], 1942\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *\u2020''S. etruscus'' (Falconer, 1868) Etruscan rhinoceros\n*\u2020''S. jeanvireti'' (Falconer, 1859)\n*\u2020''S. hundsheimensis'' (Toula, 1902) Hundsheim rhinoceros\n*\u2020''S. hemitoechus'' (Falconer, 1859) Narrow-nosed rhinoceros\n*\u2020''S. kirchbergensis'' (J\u00e4ger, 1839) Merck's rhinoceros\n}}\n\n'''''Stephanorhinus''''' is an [[extinct]] genus of two-horned [[rhinoceros]] native to northern [[Eurasia]] and possibly North Africa that lived during the [[Pliocene]] to [[Late Pleistocene]]. Two species of ''Stephanorhinus'', [[Merck's rhinoceros]] ''S. kirchbergensis'' and the narrow-nosed rhinoceros ''S. hemitoechus'' persisted into the [[Last Glacial Period|last glacial period]], with the last record for the latter being around 40,000 years ago in [[Bacho Kiro cave]] in Bulgaria.<ref>Stuart, A.J., Lister, A.M., 2007. Patterns of Late Quaternary megafaunal extinctions in Europe and northern Asia. In: Kahlke, R.-D., Maul, L.C., Mazza, P. (Eds.), Late Neogene and Quaternary Biodiversity and Evolution: Regional Developments and Interregional Correlations Vol. II, Proceedings of the 18th International Senckenberg Conference (VI International Palaeontological Colloquium in Weimar). Courier Forschungsinstitut Senckenberg 259, pp. 287-297.</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe first part of the name is derived from that of [[Stephen I of Hungary|King Stephen I of Hungary]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Tong|first=HaoWen|last2=Wu|first2=XianZhu|date=April 2010|title=Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia) from the Rhino Cave in Shennongjia, Hubei|journal=Chinese Science Bulletin|language=en|volume=55|issue=12|pages=1157\u20131168|bibcode=2010ChSBu..55.1157T|doi=10.1007/s11434-010-0050-5|issn=1001-6538}}</ref> and the second part from ''''rhinos'''' (\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2, meaning \"[[nose]]\"), as with ''Dicerorhinus.''\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe taxonomic history of ''Stephanorhinus'' is long and convoluted, as many species are known by numerous synonyms and different genera, typically ''Rhinoceros'' and ''Dicerorhinus'' for the 19th and most of the early 20th century. The genus was named by [[Mikl\u00f3s Kretzoi]] in 1942.<ref>Mikl\u00f3s Kretzoi: ''[http://epa.oszk.hu/01600/01635/00420/pdf/ Bemerkungen zur System der Nachmioz\u00e4nen Nashorn-Gattungen (Comments on the system of the post Miocene rhinoceros genera)]''  [[F\u00f6ldtani K\u00f6zl\u00f6ny|F\u00f6ldtani K\u00f6zl\u00f6ni]], Budapest 72 (4-12), 1942, S. 309\u2013318</ref> It is thought that ''Stephanorhinus'' is more closely related to the [[Sumatran rhinoceros]] and [[woolly rhinoceros]] than other rhino species. A complete mitochondrial genome of ''S. kirchbergensis'' obtained from a 70,000 - 48,000 year old skull preserved in permafrost in arctic [[Yakutia]] showed that it was more closely related to the woolly rhinoceros than the Sumatran rhinoceros.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kirillova|first=Irina V.|last2=Chernova|first2=Olga F.|last3=van der Made|first3=Jan|last4=Kukarskih|first4=Vladimir V.|last5=Shapiro|first5=Beth|last6=van der Plicht|first6=Johannes|last7=Shidlovskiy|first7=Fedor K.|last8=Heintzman|first8=Peter D.|last9=van Kolfschoten|first9=Thijs|last10=Zanina|first10=Oksana G.|date=November 2017|title=Discovery of the skull of Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis (J\u00e4ger, 1839) above the Arctic Circle|journal=Quaternary Research|language=en|volume=88|issue=3|pages=537\u2013550|bibcode=2017QuRes..88..537K|doi=10.1017/qua.2017.53|issn=0033-5894}}</ref>  In 2019 a study of dental proteomes showed that the genus was [[Paraphyly|paraphyletic]] as currently defined, as the genus ''[[Coelodonta]]'' was found to be derived from an early diverging lineage within ''Stephanorhinus'', with the proteome sequence obtained from the enamel of a 1.77 million year old ''Stephanorhinus'' sp''.'' tooth from [[Dmanisi historic site|Dmanisi]] outside the clade containing the woolly rhinoceros and ''S. kirchbergensis.''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cappellini|first=Enrico|last2=Welker|first2=Frido|last3=Pandolfi|first3=Luca|last4=Ramos-Madrigal|first4=Jazm\u00edn|last5=Samodova|first5=Diana|last6=R\u00fcther|first6=Patrick L.|last7=Fotakis|first7=Anna K.|last8=Lyon|first8=David|last9=Moreno-Mayar|first9=J. V\u00edctor|last10=Bukhsianidze|first10=Maia|last11=Rakownikow Jersie-Christensen|first11=Rosa|displayauthors=10|date=October 2019|title=Early Pleistocene enamel proteome from Dmanisi resolves Stephanorhinus phylogeny|url=|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=574|issue=7776|pages=103\u2013107|doi=10.1038/s41586-019-1555-y|issn=0028-0836|pmc=6894936|pmid=31511700|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Species and evolution==\nThe oldest known species of the genus are from the Pliocene of Europe, the species ''S. pikermiensis'' and ''S. megarhinus'' that were formerly considered to belong to ''Stephanorhinus'' are currently considered to belong to ''[[Dihoplus]].''<ref name=\":2\">{{Citation|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|title=Evolutionary history of Rhinocerotina  (Mammalia, Perissodactyla)|date=2018|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.32774/fosreppal.20.1810.102732|work=Fossilia - Reports in Palaeontology|pages=27\u201332|publisher=Saverio Bartolini Lucenti|isbn=979-12-200-3408-1|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Rivals|first2=Florent|last3=Rabinovich|first3=Rivka|date=January 2020|title=A new species of rhinoceros from the site of Bethlehem: \u2018Dihoplus\u2019 bethlehemsis sp. nov. (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1040618220300124|journal=Quaternary International|language=en|volume=537|pages=48\u201360|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2020.01.011}}</ref>\n[[File:Stephanorhinus jeanvireti skull.jpg|left|thumb|Skull of ''Stephanorhinus jeanvireti'']]\n''Stephanorhinus jeanvireti,'' also known as ''S. elatus''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ballatore|first=Manuel|last2=Breda|first2=Marzia|date=December 2016|title=Stephanorhinus elatus (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia): proposal for the conservation of the earlier specific name and designation of a lectotype|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/10.5252/g2016n4a7|journal=Geodiversitas|language=en|volume=38|issue=4|pages=579\u2013594|doi=10.5252/g2016n4a7|issn=1280-9659}}</ref> Is known from the Late Pliocene and Early Pleistocene of Europe. Its remains are relatively rare in comparison to other ''Stephanorhinus'' species. Specimens are known from the Late Pliocene of Germany<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lacombat|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last2=M\u00f6rs|first2=Thomas|date=2008-08-01|title=The northernmost occurrence of the rare Late Pliocene rhinoceros Stephanorhinus jeanvireti (Mammalia, Perissodactyla)|url=http://openurl.ingenta.com/content/xref?genre=article&issn=0077-7749&volume=249&issue=2&spage=157|journal=Neues Jahrbuch f\u00fcr Geologie und Pal\u00e4ontologie - Abhandlungen|language=en|volume=249|issue=2|pages=157\u2013165|doi=10.1127/0077-7749/2008/0249-0157}}</ref> France, Italy,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|date=October 2013|title=New and revised occurrences of Dihoplus megarhinus (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) in the Pliocene of Italy|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s13358-013-0056-0|journal=Swiss Journal of Palaeontology|volume=132|issue=2|pages=239\u2013255|doi=10.1007/s13358-013-0056-0|issn=1664-2376}}</ref> Slovakia<ref>\u0160ujan, M., Ryb\u00e1r, S., \u0160arinov\u00e1, K., Kov\u00e1\u010d, M., Vla\u010diky, M., Zervanov\u00e1, J., 2013. [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236974033_Uppermost_Miocene_to_Quaternary_accumulation_history_at_the_Danube_Basin_eastern_flanks Uppermost Miocene to Quaternary accumulation history at the Danube Basin eastern flanks], in: Fodor, L., K\u00f6v\u00e9r, Sz. (eds.), 11th Meeting of the Central European Tectonic Studies Group (CETeG). Abstract book, Geol. Geophys. Inst. of Hungary, Budapest, pp. 66-68.</ref> and Greece,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=Claude|last2=Tsoukala|first2=Evangelia|date=June 2013|title=The Tapiridae, Rhinocerotidae and Suidae (Mammalia) of the Early Villafranchian site of Milia (Grevena, Macedonia, Greece)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.5252/g2013n2a7|journal=Geodiversitas|volume=35|issue=2|pages=447\u2013489|doi=10.5252/g2013n2a7|issn=1280-9659}}</ref> and the Early Pleistocene of Romania.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Codrea|first2=Vlad A.|last3=Popescu|first3=Aurelian|date=December 2019|title=Stephanorhinus jeanvireti (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) from the early Pleistocene of Col\u021be\u0219ti (southwestern Romania)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1631068319301319|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=18|issue=8|pages=1041\u20131056|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2019.07.004}}</ref>[[File:Stephanorhinus etruscus skull.JPG|left|thumb|Skull of  ''Stephanorhinus etruscus'']]''Stephanorhinus etruscus'' first appears in the latest Pliocene in the Iberian Peninsula, around 3.3 Ma at [[:es:Yacimiento de Las Higueruelas|Las Higueruelas]] in Spain and before 3 Ma at [[Piedrabuena]], and during the latest Pliocene at Villafranca d\u2019Asti and Castelnuovo di Barardenga in Italy and is abundant during most of the [[Villafranchian]] period in Europe, and is the sole rhinoceros species in Europe between 2.5 to around 1.3 Ma. A specimen is known from the Early Pleistocene (1.6-1.2 Ma) [[Ubeidiya]] locality in Israel. During the late Early Pleistocene it is largely replaced by ''S. hundsheimensis''. The last known records of the species are from the latest Early Pleistocene of the Iberian peninsula, around 0.9-0.8 Ma.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Cerde\u00f1o|first2=Esperanza|last3=Codrea|first3=Vlad|last4=Kotsakis|first4=Tassos|date=September 2017|title=Biogeography and chronology of the Eurasian extinct rhinoceros Stephanorhinus etruscus (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1631068317300702|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=16|issue=7|pages=762\u2013773|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2017.06.004}}</ref>\n\n''Stephanorhinus yunchuchenensis'' is known from a single specimen in Early Pleistocene deposits in [[Yushe County]], [[Shaanxi]] while ''Stephanorhinus lantianensis'' is also known from a single specimen from late Early Pleistocene (1.15 Ma) deposits in [[Lantian County]], Shaanxi.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Tong|first=Hao-wen|date=November 2012|title=Evolution of the non-Coelodonta dicerorhine lineage in China|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1631068312000838|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=11|issue=8|pages=555\u2013562|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2012.06.002}}</ref> These are stated to be synonyms of ''Stephanorhinus'' ''kirchbergensis'' by some sources.<ref name=\"Antoine 2011\" />\n\nThe first record of ''Stephanorhinus'' ''kirchbergensis'' is in China at [[Zhoukoudian|Choukoutien]] Locality 13, in [[Fangshan District]] near Beijing which is around the Early-Mid Pleistocene transition at 0.8 Ma.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis skull.jpg|left|thumb|Skull of ''Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis'']]\n''Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis'' first defintively appears in the fossil record in Europe and Anatolia at around 1.2 Ma, with possible records in Iberia around 1.6 Ma and 1.4-1.3 Ma. The earliest confirmed appearance in Italy around 1 Ma.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pandolfi|first=Luca|last2=Erten|first2=H\u00fcseyin|date=January 2017|title=Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) from the late early Pleistocene deposits of the Denizli Basin (Anatolia, Turkey)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0016699516301243|journal=Geobios|language=en|volume=50|issue=1|pages=65\u201373|doi=10.1016/j.geobios.2016.10.002}}</ref> The diet of ''S. hundsheimensis'' was flexible and ungeneralised, with two different early Middle Pleistocene populations under different climactic regimes having tooth wear analyses suggesting contrasting browsing and grazing habits.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kahlke|first=Ralf-Dietrich|last2=Kaiser|first2=Thomas M.|date=August 2011|title=Generalism as a subsistence strategy: advantages and limitations of the highly flexible feeding traits of Pleistocene Stephanorhinus hundsheimensis (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0277379109004314|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=30|issue=17-18|pages=2250\u20132261|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2009.12.012}}</ref> The more specialised ''S. kirchbergensis'' and ''S. hemiotoechus'',, appear in Europe between 0.7-6 Ma and 0.6-0.5 Ma respectively, and largely displace ''S. hundsheimensis. S. kirchbergensis'' and ''S. hemiotoechus'' are typically interpreted as a browsing form and grazing form, respectively. The evolution of more specialized diets is possibly due to the change to the 100 Kyr cycle after the [[Mid-Pleistocene Transition|Mid Pleistocene Transition]], which resulted in environmental stability allowing the development of more specialsed forms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Asperen|first=Eline N.|last2=Kahlke|first2=Ralf-Dietrich|date=January 2015|title=Dietary variation and overlap in Central and Northwest European Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis and S. hemitoechus (Rhinocerotidae, Mammalia) influenced by habitat diversity|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0277379114003886|journal=Quaternary Science Reviews|language=en|volume=107|pages=47\u201361|doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2014.10.001}}</ref>\n[[File:Skulls of pleistocene rhinos.png|left|thumb|Skulls from top to bottom. ''S. kirchbergensis, S. hemitoechus'' and the woolly rhinoceros, showing the difference in head angle]]\n\nFrom the late Middle Pleistocene onwards, the large Merck's rhinoceros (''[[Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis]]'') and the narrow-nosed rhinoceros (''[[Stephanorhinus hemitoechus]]'') were the only species of ''Stephanorhinus''. ''Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis'' preferred forest or woodland habitats, while ''S. hemitoechus'' was probably adapted to more open habitats.<ref name=\"Pushkina 2007\">Diana Pushkina: ''The Pleistocene easternmost distribution in Eurasia of the species associated with the Eemian'' Palaeoloxodon antiquus ''assemblage.'' Mammal Review, 2007.\nVolume 37 Issue 3, Pages 224 - 245</ref> ''S. kirchbergensis'' is relatively rare in fossil record and known from few Italian, French, German, British, and East-European localities, mostly of the middle Pleistocene. In Asia it is known from [[Siberia]], [[Central Asia]] (e.g. southeastern [[Kazakhstan]]), [[Central Korea]], and [[China]]. It may have also occurred in [[Israel]] and [[Lebanon]], but here it is unclear if it was really ''S. kirchbergensis'' or a similar species.<ref>Emmanuel M.E. Billia: ''Revision of the fossil material attributed to ''Stephanorhinus kirchbergensis'' (J\u00e4ger 1839) (Mammalia, Rhinocerotidae) preserved in the museum collections of the Russian Federation''. Quaternary International. Volume 179, Issue 1, March 2008, Pages 25-37</ref> In [[eastern China]], ''S. kirchbergensis'' was present throughout the Pleistocene between 30\u00b0N and 40\u00b0N.<ref name=\"Antoine 2011\">Pierre Olivier Antoine: ''Pleistocene and holocene rhinocerotids (Mammalia, Perissodactyla) from the Indochinese Peninsula.'' In: ''Comptes Rendus Palevol.'' 2011, S. 1\u201310.</ref> It is stated by some sources that ''S. hemitoechus'' occurs in North Africa.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn eastern Europe ''S. kirchbergensis'' disappeared during the earliest Late Pleistocene, where it is recorded in the [[Eemian]] in Poland. In the forests of the [[Caucasus]] it may have survived even until the early [[Weichselian]]. The last occurrences are known from [[Spain]], where it survived until the middle or early Late Weichselian. The narrow-nosed rhinoceros appeared in Europe in the early Middle Pleistocene. It is known here from many localities between, Spain, [[Italy]], [[Germany]] and the [[British Islands]]. Apart from Europe it is also known from [[Syria]], Israel, the Caucasus and from one Late Pleistocene locality close to [[Lake Baikal]]. This is the easternmost point of the known range. The latest fossils of the narrow-nosed rhinoceros are known from the [[Balkans]], where it survived until the early late Weichselian.<ref name=\"Pushkina 2007\"/>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14551210}}\n\n[[Category:Pleistocene rhinoceroses]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene genus extinctions]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric mammals of Europe]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Hemiauchenia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephanorhinus"}
{"title_page": "Nehal Hashmi", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| name                = Nehal Ahmed Hashmi\n| office              = Member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]]\n| term_start          = 12 March 2015\n| term_end            = 1 February 2018\n| successor           = [[Asad Ashraf]]\n| constituency        = General seat from [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1960|1|28|df=y}}\n| nationality         = Pakistani\n| party               = [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]]\n}}\n\n'''Nehal Ahmed Hashmi''' ({{Lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0646\u06c1\u0627\u0644 \u06c1\u0627\u0634\u0645\u06cc}}}}; born 28 January 1960) is a Pakistani politician who has been a member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]], from March 2015 to February 2018.\n\n==Early life==\nHashmi was born on 28 January 1960 in an Urdu-speaking family hailing from the Bihar district of India.\nHe was a prominent student leader and founded his own political organistaion by the name of All Pakistan Youth Wing, and served as its president before joining PML-N in 1992.<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\">{{cite news|title=Zubair Umar emerges as top candidate to become 32nd governor of Sindh|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2017/01/28/zubair-umar-emerges-as-top-candidate-to-become-32nd-governor-of-sindh/|accessdate=31 May 2017|publisher=Pakistan Today|date=28 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131174309/http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2017/01/28/zubair-umar-emerges-as-top-candidate-to-become-32nd-governor-of-sindh/|archivedate=31 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHashmi is a renowned criminal lawyer in Karachi circuit and started practicing law in the late 1980s.In his early days as a lawyer, he became known for filling petition on social and public issue and earned the title of \"Mr Petitioner\" amongst the masses. He has been associated with some of the most prominent cases, such as the Murtaza Bhutto tribunal and former PM Nawaz Sharif's NAB case in 1999.<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\" />\n\n==Political career==\n\nHashmi was the advier to Prime Minister of Pakistan [[Muhammad Nawaz Sharif]] on Law Justice and Human Rights from 1997 to 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six new faces reach the upper house|url=https://nation.com.pk/06-Mar-2015/six-new-faces-reach-the-upper-house|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Nation|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://nation.com.pk/06-Mar-2015/six-new-faces-reach-the-upper-house|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was serving as the President of [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] (PML-N) chapter in Karachi<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\" /> during 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Men from Pakistan Movement honoured on nation's 66th Independence Day - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/422227/men-from-pakistan-movement-honoured-on-nations-66th-independence-day/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Express Tribune|date=15 August 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820222400/http://tribune.com.pk/story/422227/men-from-pakistan-movement-honoured-on-nations-66th-independence-day/|archivedate=20 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, he was appointed as the General Secretary of PML-N chapter in Sindh.<ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N Sindh decides to appoint officials, not elect them - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/743062/pml-n-sindh-decides-to-appoint-officials-not-elect-them/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Express Tribune|date=2 August 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808055931/http://tribune.com.pk/story/743062/pml-n-sindh-decides-to-appoint-officials-not-elect-them/|archivedate=8 August 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, he was re-appointed as the General Secretary of PML-N Sindh.<ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N dissolves provincial body|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/532224-pml-n-dissolves-provincial-body|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/532224-pml-n-dissolves-provincial-body|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected to the [[Senate of Pakistan]] on general seat from Punjab as a candidate of PML-N in [[2015 Pakistani Senate election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Unofficial results pour in as voting comes to a close - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/848196/live-polling-for-senate-elections-underway/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=5 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622104254/https://tribune.com.pk/story/848196/live-polling-for-senate-elections-underway/|archivedate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N sweeps Punjab; PPP, MQM recapture Sindh in Senate polls|url=https://arynews.tv/en/voting-time-senate-election-ends/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=ARYNEWS|language=en-us|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907045854/https://arynews.tv/en/voting-time-senate-election-ends/|archivedate=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PPP leads Pakistan Senate vote {{!}} SAMAA TV|url=https://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2015/03/ruling-pmln-leads-pakistan-senate-vote/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=Samaa TV|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001093551/http://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2015/03/ruling-pmln-leads-pakistan-senate-vote/|archivedate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate Election: Unofficial Results|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/2135-senate-election-unofficial-results|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824180801/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/2135-senate-election-unofficial-results|archivedate=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate Elections 2015: PML-N, PPP almost get equal representation in upper house {{!}} Pakistan {{!}} Dunya News|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/265570-Senate-Elections-2015-PMLN-PPP-almost-get-equal|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=dunyanews.tv|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916145609/http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/265570-Senate-Elections-2015-PMLN-PPP-almost-get-equal|archivedate=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as the advisor to the Prime Minister of Pakistan on law, justice and human rights.<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\" />\n\nIn May 2017, his membership in PML-N was suspended and he was asked to resign from the membership of Senate by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif for violating the party discipline.<ref>{{cite news|title=PM asks Nehal Hashmi to resign from senatorship {{!}} SAMAA TV|url=https://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2017/05/pm-asks-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-as-senator/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=Samaa TV|date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531170409/https://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2017/05/pm-asks-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-as-senator/|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PM Nawaz directs Nehal Hashmi to resign from Senate|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-pm-nawaz-directs-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-from-senate|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.geo.tv|date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531135805/https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-pm-nawaz-directs-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-from-senate|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N senator threatens consequences for those 'grilling' Hussain Nawaz|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1336533/pml-n-senator-threatens-consequences-for-those-grilling-hussain-nawaz|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=31 May 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531121303/https://www.dawn.com/news/1336533/pml-n-senator-threatens-consequences-for-those-grilling-hussain-nawaz|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senator Nehal Hashmi quits after threatening speech|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/207796-Nehal-Hashmi-asked-to-quit-after-threatening-speech|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.thenews.com.pk|date=31 May 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531175411/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/207796-Nehal-Hashmi-asked-to-quit-after-threatening-speech|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> After which he announced to resign from the Senate.<ref>{{cite news|title=CJP takes suo motu notice of Nehal Hashmi's speech|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-cjp-takes-suo-motu-notice-of-nehal-hashmis-speech|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.geo.tv|date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531142912/https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-cjp-takes-suo-motu-notice-of-nehal-hashmis-speech|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, he withdrew his resignation from Senate after a meeting with the chairman of the Senate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guramani|first1=Nadir|title=Hashmi withdraws resignation from Senate|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1337771/hashmi-withdraws-resignation-from-senate|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=6 June 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606080809/https://www.dawn.com/news/1337771/hashmi-withdraws-resignation-from-senate|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2018, Hashmi was convicted by the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]] in a contempt of court case. He was sentenced to one month imprisonment, and was barred from holding public office for a period of next five years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Contempt case: SC bars Nehal Hashmi from holding public office for five years|url=https://nation.com.pk/01-Feb-2018/contempt-case-sc-bars-nehal-hashmi-from-holding-public-office-for-five-years|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Nation|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://nation.com.pk/01-Feb-2018/contempt-case-sc-bars-nehal-hashmi-from-holding-public-office-for-five-years|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nehal Hashmi sentenced to one month jail time in contempt of court case - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1623555/1-nehal-hashmi-sentenced-one-month-jail-time-contempt-court-case/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Express Tribune|date=1 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1623555/1-nehal-hashmi-sentenced-one-month-jail-time-contempt-court-case/|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref> On the same day, he ceased to be a member of the Senate<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chaudhry|first1=Fahad|title=Nehal Hashmi disqualified from Senate|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1386845/nehal-hashmi-disqualified-from-senate|accessdate=2 February 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=2 February 2018}}</ref> and was arrested.<ref>{{cite news|title=PMLN Senator Nihal Hashmi sentenced to 1 month jail in contempt case|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/275727-pmln-senator-nihal-hashmi-sentenced-to-1-month-in-jail-for-contempt-of-court|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/275727-pmln-senator-nihal-hashmi-sentenced-to-1-month-in-jail-for-contempt-of-court|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref> He was released from jail after a month on 28 February.<ref>{{cite news|title='I've been made a victim of revenge,' says Nehal Hashmi upon release from Adiala Jail|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1392288/ive-been-made-a-victim-of-revenge-says-nehal-hashmi-upon-release-from-adiala-jail|accessdate=28 February 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hashmi, Nehal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani senators (14th Parliament)]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Muslim League (N) politicians]]\n[[Category:Pakistani lawyers]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Karachi]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Pakistani prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People expelled from public office]]\n[[Category:Pakistani politicians convicted of crimes]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               =Nehal Hashmi\n|office = Member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]]\n|term_start         =  12 March 2015\n|term_end = 1 February 2018\n|successor = [[Asad Ashraf]]\n|constituency = General seat from [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|birth_date  =  {{birth date and age|1960|1|28|df=y}}\n|nationality     = Pakistani\n|party           = [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]]\n}}\n\n'''Syed Nehal Hashmi''' ({{Lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0646\u06c1\u0627\u0644 \u06c1\u0627\u0634\u0645\u06cc}}}}; born 28 January 1960) is a Pakistani politician who has been a member of the [[Senate of Pakistan]], from March 2015 to February 2018.\n\n==Early life==\nHashmi was born on 28 January 1960 in an Urdu-speaking family hailing from the Bihar district of India.\nHe was a prominent student leader and founded his own political organistaion by the name of All Pakistan Youth Wing, and served as its president before joining PML-N in 1992.<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\">{{cite news|title=Zubair Umar emerges as top candidate to become 32nd governor of Sindh|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2017/01/28/zubair-umar-emerges-as-top-candidate-to-become-32nd-governor-of-sindh/|accessdate=31 May 2017|publisher=Pakistan Today|date=28 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131174309/http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2017/01/28/zubair-umar-emerges-as-top-candidate-to-become-32nd-governor-of-sindh/|archivedate=31 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHashmi is a renowned criminal lawyer in Karachi circuit and started practicing law in the late 1980s.In his early days as a lawyer, he became known for filling petition on social and public issue and earned the title of \"Mr Petitioner\" amongst the masses. He has been associated with some of the most prominent cases, such as the Murtaza Bhutto tribunal and former PM Nawaz Sharif's NAB case in 1999.<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\" />\n\n==Political career==\n\nHashmi was the advier to Prime Minister of Pakistan [[Muhammad Nawaz Sharif]] on Law Justice and Human Rights from 1997 to 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six new faces reach the upper house|url=https://nation.com.pk/06-Mar-2015/six-new-faces-reach-the-upper-house|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Nation|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://nation.com.pk/06-Mar-2015/six-new-faces-reach-the-upper-house|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was serving as the President of [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] (PML-N) chapter in Karachi<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\" /> during 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Men from Pakistan Movement honoured on nation's 66th Independence Day - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/422227/men-from-pakistan-movement-honoured-on-nations-66th-independence-day/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Express Tribune|date=15 August 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820222400/http://tribune.com.pk/story/422227/men-from-pakistan-movement-honoured-on-nations-66th-independence-day/|archivedate=20 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, he was appointed as the General Secretary of PML-N chapter in Sindh.<ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N Sindh decides to appoint officials, not elect them - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/743062/pml-n-sindh-decides-to-appoint-officials-not-elect-them/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Express Tribune|date=2 August 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808055931/http://tribune.com.pk/story/743062/pml-n-sindh-decides-to-appoint-officials-not-elect-them/|archivedate=8 August 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, he was re-appointed as the General Secretary of PML-N Sindh.<ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N dissolves provincial body|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/532224-pml-n-dissolves-provincial-body|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/532224-pml-n-dissolves-provincial-body|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected to the [[Senate of Pakistan]] on general seat from Punjab as a candidate of PML-N in [[2015 Pakistani Senate election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Unofficial results pour in as voting comes to a close - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/848196/live-polling-for-senate-elections-underway/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=5 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622104254/https://tribune.com.pk/story/848196/live-polling-for-senate-elections-underway/|archivedate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N sweeps Punjab; PPP, MQM recapture Sindh in Senate polls|url=https://arynews.tv/en/voting-time-senate-election-ends/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=ARYNEWS|language=en-us|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907045854/https://arynews.tv/en/voting-time-senate-election-ends/|archivedate=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PPP leads Pakistan Senate vote {{!}} SAMAA TV|url=https://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2015/03/ruling-pmln-leads-pakistan-senate-vote/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=Samaa TV|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001093551/http://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2015/03/ruling-pmln-leads-pakistan-senate-vote/|archivedate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate Election: Unofficial Results|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/2135-senate-election-unofficial-results|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824180801/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/2135-senate-election-unofficial-results|archivedate=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senate Elections 2015: PML-N, PPP almost get equal representation in upper house {{!}} Pakistan {{!}} Dunya News|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/265570-Senate-Elections-2015-PMLN-PPP-almost-get-equal|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=dunyanews.tv|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916145609/http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/265570-Senate-Elections-2015-PMLN-PPP-almost-get-equal|archivedate=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as the advisor to the Prime Minister of Pakistan on law, justice and human rights.<ref name=\"pakistantoday/28jan2017\" />\n\nIn May 2017, his membership in PML-N was suspended and he was asked to resign from the membership of Senate by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif for violating the party discipline.<ref>{{cite news|title=PM asks Nehal Hashmi to resign from senatorship {{!}} SAMAA TV|url=https://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2017/05/pm-asks-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-as-senator/|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=Samaa TV|date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531170409/https://www.samaa.tv/pakistan/2017/05/pm-asks-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-as-senator/|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PM Nawaz directs Nehal Hashmi to resign from Senate|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-pm-nawaz-directs-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-from-senate|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.geo.tv|date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531135805/https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-pm-nawaz-directs-nehal-hashmi-to-resign-from-senate|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PML-N senator threatens consequences for those 'grilling' Hussain Nawaz|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1336533/pml-n-senator-threatens-consequences-for-those-grilling-hussain-nawaz|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=31 May 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531121303/https://www.dawn.com/news/1336533/pml-n-senator-threatens-consequences-for-those-grilling-hussain-nawaz|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Senator Nehal Hashmi quits after threatening speech|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/207796-Nehal-Hashmi-asked-to-quit-after-threatening-speech|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.thenews.com.pk|date=31 May 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531175411/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/207796-Nehal-Hashmi-asked-to-quit-after-threatening-speech|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> After which he announced to resign from the Senate.<ref>{{cite news|title=CJP takes suo motu notice of Nehal Hashmi's speech|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-cjp-takes-suo-motu-notice-of-nehal-hashmis-speech|accessdate=31 May 2017|work=www.geo.tv|date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531142912/https://www.geo.tv/latest/144064-cjp-takes-suo-motu-notice-of-nehal-hashmis-speech|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, he withdrew his resignation from Senate after a meeting with the chairman of the Senate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guramani|first1=Nadir|title=Hashmi withdraws resignation from Senate|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1337771/hashmi-withdraws-resignation-from-senate|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=6 June 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606080809/https://www.dawn.com/news/1337771/hashmi-withdraws-resignation-from-senate|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2018, Hashmi was convicted by the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan]] in a contempt of court case. He was sentenced to one month imprisonment, and was barred from holding public office for a period of next five years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Contempt case: SC bars Nehal Hashmi from holding public office for five years|url=https://nation.com.pk/01-Feb-2018/contempt-case-sc-bars-nehal-hashmi-from-holding-public-office-for-five-years|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Nation|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://nation.com.pk/01-Feb-2018/contempt-case-sc-bars-nehal-hashmi-from-holding-public-office-for-five-years|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nehal Hashmi sentenced to one month jail time in contempt of court case - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1623555/1-nehal-hashmi-sentenced-one-month-jail-time-contempt-court-case/|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=The Express Tribune|date=1 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://tribune.com.pk/story/1623555/1-nehal-hashmi-sentenced-one-month-jail-time-contempt-court-case/|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref> On the same day, he ceased to be a member of the Senate<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chaudhry|first1=Fahad|title=Nehal Hashmi disqualified from Senate|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1386845/nehal-hashmi-disqualified-from-senate|accessdate=2 February 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=2 February 2018}}</ref> and was arrested.<ref>{{cite news|title=PMLN Senator Nihal Hashmi sentenced to 1 month jail in contempt case|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/275727-pmln-senator-nihal-hashmi-sentenced-to-1-month-in-jail-for-contempt-of-court|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=www.thenews.com.pk|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201081142/https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/275727-pmln-senator-nihal-hashmi-sentenced-to-1-month-in-jail-for-contempt-of-court|archivedate=1 February 2018}}</ref> He was released from jail after a month on 28 February.<ref>{{cite news|title='I've been made a victim of revenge,' says Nehal Hashmi upon release from Adiala Jail|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1392288/ive-been-made-a-victim-of-revenge-says-nehal-hashmi-upon-release-from-adiala-jail|accessdate=28 February 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3